"a.狡猾的，鬼鬼祟祟的 【英】 adj.秘密的,鬼鬼祟祟 的(clever in deceiving) 【考】 反义词：artless(朴 实的) adj. 狡诈虚伪的 【记】死赖－死赖在你们家要钱－狡诈虚伪的 【反】artless(adj 朴实的); ingenuous(adj 坦白直率的) 【记】spy的特点 sly (adj.)  c.1200, ""skillful, clever, dexterous,"" from Old Norse sloegr ""cunning, crafty, sly,"" from Proto-Germanic *slogis (cognates: Low German slu ""cunning, sly,"" German schlau), probably from base *slak- ""to strike, hit"" (see slay (v.)), with an original notion of ""able to hit."" Compare German verschlagen ""cunning, crafty, sly,"" schlagfertig ""quick-witted,"" literally ""strike-ready,"" from schlagen ""to strike."" A non-pejorative use of the word lingered in northern English dialect until 20c. On the sly ""in secret"" is recorded from 1812. Sly-boots ""a seeming Silly, but subtil Fellow"" is in the 1700 ""Dictionary of the Canting Crew."""
